{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01CibY8JTsELBpYbrcirV87t","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_011Y2nD1WR1JNw4J357tFrFY","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Scoring model assigns correct risk score when transaction exceeds configured amount threshold","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior depends on configured thresholds being loaded and applied correctly. A unit test with mocked configuration ('return threshold=1000') bypasses a common real-world failure: configuration loaded from the wrong source or with wrong values. To catch configuration-loading bugs, the test must load thresholds from the actual config system (file, database, or service). The scoring logic itself is deterministic, but configuration delivery is not — this is why we need the integrated system.","test_description":"Load amount thresholds from the configuration system for multiple merchant categories. Create transactions with amounts at, below, and above each threshold. Verify risk scores increase when transaction amount exceeds its merchant category's configured threshold. Include boundary-condition tests (amount exactly equals threshold).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Risk model identifies fraudulent pattern (rapid small purchases from different geographies) even when no single rule exceeds thresholds","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This behavior tests the risk model's actual classification capability—its ability to detect a pattern that rule-based scoring misses. Mocking the risk model (always returning high fraud probability when criteria are met) tests your mock's logic, not the model's real pattern-detection ability. A real failure would be 'the model fails to detect this pattern', which only a real model can expose. Because fraud detection in practice depends on the model's real learned behavior, not simulated behavior, this requires the actual model.","test_description":"Create a transaction sequence exhibiting the pattern: 3–5 small purchases from different geographic locations within a short time window (e.g., 2 hours), where each purchase amount is below the scoring model's individual rule thresholds. Run the real risk model on this sequence. Verify the model's fraud probability output exceeds the classification threshold, indicating detected fraud. Confirm the scoring model alone does NOT flag this pattern (to show the risk model catches what rules miss).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Velocity check correctly counts transactions within configured time window per user","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The velocity check must query transactions from persistent storage (database), filter by user and time window, and count. A unit test with mocked transaction lists ('return these 5 transactions') misses real failures: wrong database query, time-zone issues, or transactions from other users leaking into the count. To catch query-layer failures, the test must hit the real transaction storage. The counting logic itself is simple, but transaction retrieval is where real bugs hide.","test_description":"Create actual transaction records in the database for two different users, with multiple transactions per user at varying times—some within the configured time window (e.g., last 5 minutes) and some outside. Run the velocity check for one user. Verify the count reflects only that user's transactions within the window. Verify transactions from other users are excluded and transactions outside the time window are excluded. Test boundary cases (transaction at exact window start/end time).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Transaction flagged by risk model but not scoring model is held for review (OR gate)","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This behavior tests that the system correctly implements an OR gate: if *either* model flags a transaction, it is held. A unit test using mocked models (risk='fraud', scoring='safe', verify held=true) tests the OR logic, not whether the real models' outputs drive the decision. Real-world failures include: one model's output is ignored, or the combining logic is wrong. To catch these, you must observe real model outputs actually driving the hold decision. Since the risk model is agentic (behavior #2), any test that depends on its real output is also agentic.","test_description":"Create test transactions and run both the real scoring and risk models on each. Test all four combinations: (risk='fraud', scoring='safe'), (risk='safe', scoring='fraud'), (risk='fraud', scoring='fraud'), (risk='safe', scoring='safe'). Verify that the transaction is held for manual review in the first three cases and released in the fourth. Confirm that if risk model flags it alone, it is held even if scoring model does not flag it.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.6,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Combined output includes both numeric risk score and risk model's fraud probability","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This behavior verifies the output structure includes data from both models. A unit test with mocked models can verify the combining code correctly assembles a JSON object with both fields. However, a real failure is more subtle: the output is missing a field, or the field is null/invalid because the underlying model call failed. To catch failures in how real model outputs are captured and included, you need both models to run and produce actual outputs. The risk model is agentic (behavior #2), so any integration test that depends on its real output is agentic.","test_description":"Run both the scoring and risk models on a transaction. Inspect the combined output JSON. Verify it includes: (1) the numeric risk score from the scoring model (non-null, valid range), (2) the fraud probability from the risk model (non-null, valid range 0.0–1.0). Verify both fields are present and correctly labeled. Test that output includes metadata indicating which model flagged the transaction, if any.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.65,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13799,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13799},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4cdcea2b-25e2-4a9a-b6b3-9190978bee47","uuid":"e5cbabf7-0893-45d2-b05c-ce33ba76100c"}
